'''Kasuga Shrine''' (かすがじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|lt=Osaka Prefecture|Q122723|WD=Q122723|1=Osaka Prefecture}}, {{ill|lt=Ibaraki City|Q502403|WD=Q502403|1=Ibaraki, Osaka}}. It is an {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}-listed {{ill|lt=Settsu Province|Q864163|WD=Q864163|1=Settsu Province}} {{ill|lt=Shimashimo District|Q10976940|WD=Q10976940|1=Shimashimo district}} {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} and is regarded as a {{ill|lt=ronsa|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}} (shrine identified through scholarly debate).

=== History ===
One of the two seats of the Shikinaisha {{ill|lt=Sukuku Shrine|Q11664487|WD=Q11664487|1=Sukuku Shrine}}, according to the “Jingū Zōreishū,” on April 5 of {{ill|lt=Tenpyō era|Q1199879|WD=Q1199879|1=Tenpyō}} 12 ({{ill|lt=740|Q23593|WD=Q23593|1=740}}), {{ill|lt=Minister of the Right|Q1351174|WD=Q1351174|1=Minister of the Right}} {{ill|lt=Ōnakatomi no Kiyomaro|Q11431854|WD=Q11431854|lt=Nakatomi no Kiyomaro|1=Ōnakatomi no Kiyomaro}} secluded himself at this site and enshrined his ancestral deities near his residence.
* In {{ill|lt=Meireki era|Q1192766|WD=Q1192766|1=Meireki}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1655|Q6975|WD=Q6975|1=1655}}), it became independent from the affiliated villages of Moto-Sukuku-shō Village and came to be called {{ill|lt=Kasuga Shrine|Q10855011|WD=Q10855011|1=Kasuga Shrines}}.
* In {{ill|lt=Meiji era|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753|1=1872}}), it was ranked as a {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.
* On August 28, {{ill|lt=Heisei era|Q234510|WD=Q234510|1=Heisei era}} 22 ({{ill|lt=2010|Q1995|WD=Q1995|1=2010}}), a fire caused by suspected arson destroyed the main hall and worship hall.
* On March 25, Heisei 24 ({{ill|lt=2012|Q1990|WD=Q1990|1=2012}}), reconstruction of the main hall and worship hall was completed.

